'''Mii Shrine''' (みいじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Hikawa-chō Naoe, {{ill|lt=Izumo City|Q825166|WD=Q825166|1=Izumo, Shimane}}, {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|WD=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}. It is a shrine associated with traditions concerning Yagami-hime, who appears in the {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi myths|Q11433656|WD=Q11433656|1=Myth of Ōkuninushi}}, and her child {{ill|lt=Konamata-no-Kami|Q11092833|WD=Q11092833|1=Kimata-no-Kami}} (this deity), and is worshipped as a god of safe childbirth.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* Konamata-no-Kami (Mii-no-Kami)

He appears in the myths of {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōanamuchi-no-Kami|1=Ōkuninushi}} depicted in the '{{ill|lt=Kojiki|Q813031|WD=Q813031|1=Kojiki}}'. Yagami-hime, who married Ōkuninushi, became pregnant and came as far as {{ill|lt=Izumo Province|Q582846|WD=Q582846|1=Izumo Province}}, but fearing the principal wife {{ill|lt=Suseri-hime|Q8191715|WD=Q8191715|lt=Suseri-bime|1=Suseri-Hime}}, she pushed the newborn child into the fork of a tree and returned to {{ill|lt=Inaba Province|Q1054338|WD=Q1054338|1=Inaba Province}}. Because of this, the child was named Konamata-no-Kami.

=== History ===
The shrine is identified with the Mii Shrine listed as an existing government shrine (zaishingi-kan-sha) in the Izumo District entry of the '{{ill|lt=Izumo-no-Kuni Fudoki|Q11395858|WD=Q11395858|1=Izumo no Kuni Fudoki}}', and with the Mii Shrine recorded in the Izumo District of Izumo Province in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'. Near the shrine grounds, the Sugisawa III site—where nine post holes believed to be the remains of an ancient {{ill|lt=Taisha-zukuri|Q387874|WD=Q387874|1=Taisha-zukuri}} shrine building were excavated—has been discovered, and is presumed to have been the original shrine site.

=== Subsidiary and branch shrines ===
* Tenjin Shrine
* Jisson Shrine (じっそんじんじゃ) – an off-site shrine that enshrines the mother deity Yagami-hime

=== Faith ===
Near the shrine are three {{ill|lt=wells|Q43483|WD=Q43483|1=Well}} called “Ikui,” “Sakui,” and “Tsunagai,” and there is a tradition that Yagami-hime used their water for the birth bath at the time of childbirth. It is thought that worship of these three wells originally developed into the shrine.

=== References ===
